\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3b --- Bracket on featureless structural benchmarks.}{21}{section*.34}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces E3b: bracket on featureless structural benchmarks. Two $4$-regular circulant Cayley graphs disjoint-unioned with a graph-membership label (row 1), a vertex-transitive $4$-regular Cayley graph with a parity label (row 2), and two strongly regular Paley graphs with the quadratic-residue label (rows $3$--$4$). On all four, $1$-WL with constant initial features produces a single colour class ($m = 1$) for every depth $L \le 6$, so the bracket sits at the marginal-entropy ceiling ($\mathrm  {lower} = \pi $, $\mathrm  {upper} = \tfrac  {1}{2} H_{\mathrm  {bin}}(\pi )$) and \emph  {refuses to certify} a sub- random error rate on tasks that $1$-WL cannot distinguish. This is the empirical face of \cref  {cor:mpnn-bracket}: when WL is structurally blind the bound is correct and uninformative, not false and tight. Promoting these benchmarks to $2$-WL or $3$-WL is the natural next step (we leave the $k$-WL extension to a sequel). Per-row funnels in \texttt  {experiments/results/e3b.json}.}}{21}{table.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e3b}{{6}{21}{E3b: bracket on featureless structural benchmarks. Two $4$-regular circulant Cayley graphs disjoint-unioned with a graph-membership label (row 1), a vertex-transitive $4$-regular Cayley graph with a parity label (row 2), and two strongly regular Paley graphs with the quadratic-residue label (rows $3$--$4$). On all four, $1$-WL with constant initial features produces a single colour class ($m = 1$) for every depth $L \le 6$, so the bracket sits at the marginal-entropy ceiling ($\mathrm {lower} = \pi $, $\mathrm {upper} = \tfrac {1}{2} H_{\mathrm {bin}}(\pi )$) and \emph {refuses to certify} a sub- random error rate on tasks that $1$-WL cannot distinguish. This is the empirical face of \cref {cor:mpnn-bracket}: when WL is structurally blind the bound is correct and uninformative, not false and tight. Promoting these benchmarks to $2$-WL or $3$-WL is the natural next step (we leave the $k$-WL extension to a sequel). Per-row funnels in \texttt {experiments/results/e3b.json}}{table.6}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e3b@cref}{{[table][6][]6}{[1][21][]21}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3c --- Structural-vs-memorisation index and coarsened-feature audit.}{22}{section*.35}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces E3c: structural-vs-memorisation decomposition of E3 under the index $\sigma (0.05, 0.5)$, and the $m_{2}/|V|$ singleton fraction under three coarsening levels of the initial colour. \textbf  {Every E3 benchmark falls in the memorisation regime} ($\sigma \le 0$). CiteSeer and PubMed are the honest non-trivial rows: $1$-WL does not separate $\varepsilon ^{*}$ below $0.05$ at any depth ($L^{*} = \mathrm  {none}$), and the partition is genuinely sub-discrete ($m/|V| \approx 0.6$). The reviewer-grade ``trivially tight'' behaviour on ogbn-arxiv survives even 4-bin log-degree coarsening ($m_{2}/|V| = 0.85$), so the near-discrete partition is intrinsic to the graph topology, not an artefact of using raw integer degree as $h^{(0)}$ --- ogbn-arxiv \emph  {is}, by this measurement, a memorisation benchmark for $1$-WL regardless of feature resolution.}}{22}{table.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e3c}{{7}{22}{E3c: structural-vs-memorisation decomposition of E3 under the index $\sigma (0.05, 0.5)$, and the $m_{2}/|V|$ singleton fraction under three coarsening levels of the initial colour. \textbf {Every E3 benchmark falls in the memorisation regime} ($\sigma \le 0$). CiteSeer and PubMed are the honest non-trivial rows: $1$-WL does not separate $\eps ^{*}$ below $0.05$ at any depth ($L^{*} = \mathrm {none}$), and the partition is genuinely sub-discrete ($m/|V| \approx 0.6$). The reviewer-grade ``trivially tight'' behaviour on ogbn-arxiv survives even 4-bin log-degree coarsening ($m_{2}/|V| = 0.85$), so the near-discrete partition is intrinsic to the graph topology, not an artefact of using raw integer degree as $h^{(0)}$ --- ogbn-arxiv \emph {is}, by this measurement, a memorisation benchmark for $1$-WL regardless of feature resolution}{table.7}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e3c@cref}{{[table][7][]7}{[1][22][]22}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3d --- In-vivo audit of \cref  {lem:mpnn-wl-robust}.}{22}{section*.36}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3d-arch --- Post-hoc architecture-vs-WL audit (GCN/GAT/GIN $\times $ Cora/CiteSeer/PubMed, 3 seeds).}{22}{section*.37}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces E3d: \cref  {lem:mpnn-wl-robust} stress test on Cora and CiteSeer at depth $L = 3$, hidden width $32$, Xavier-initialised GIN weights. $\delta _{0}$ is the lemma's sup-norm sup$_{v \sim _{\mathrm  {WL}} w}\|h^{(0)}(v) - h^{(0)}(w)\|_{2}$ measured \emph  {empirically} on the perturbed initial features (a single per-coordinate noise std of $10^{-2}$ inflates to sup-norm $\approx 0.12$ in $\mathbb  {R}^{32}$). $D(L)$ is the empirical max embedding-diameter over WL-equivalent pairs; $\delta _{L}$ is the lemma's worst-case bound; $\gamma _{\mathrm  {eff}}^{(L)} := (D(L)/D(0))^{1/L}$ is the empirical per-round amplification factor, comparable to the worst-case sum-aggregator step $L^{c}_{\ell } + \Delta _{\max } L^{m}_{\ell }$ (here $L^{c}_{\ell } \approx (1{+}\varepsilon )\|W_{\ell }\|_{\rm  op}$, $L^{m}_{\ell } \approx \|W_{\ell }\|_{\rm  op}$, with the trainable GIN $\varepsilon \approx 0$ at random init). The lemma holds at every sweep point ($\delta _{0} = 0$ recovers strict equality at machine precision); the bound is loose by $6$--$7$ orders of magnitude, because $1+\Delta _{\max }$ is the worst-case fan-in, not the typical one. $\gamma _{\mathrm  {eff}} \approx 1.5$--$2.1$ across both graphs and all noise scales --- close to the identity per round --- suggesting that an average-degree (rather than max-degree) refinement of \cref  {lem:mpnn-wl-robust} would tighten the bound by roughly $\bigl  ((L^{c}{+}\Delta _{\max } L^{m})/\gamma _{\mathrm  {eff}}\bigr  )^{L}$ on real sparse graphs --- a $\approx 10^{6}\times $ improvement on Cora at $L=3$. We leave such a mean-Lipschitz refinement to future work; raw outputs in \texttt  {experiments/results/e3e.json}.}}{23}{table.8}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e3d}{{8}{23}{E3d: \cref {lem:mpnn-wl-robust} stress test on Cora and CiteSeer at depth $L = 3$, hidden width $32$, Xavier-initialised GIN weights. $\delta _{0}$ is the lemma's sup-norm sup$_{v \sim _{\mathrm {WL}} w}\|h^{(0)}(v) - h^{(0)}(w)\|_{2}$ measured \emph {empirically} on the perturbed initial features (a single per-coordinate noise std of $10^{-2}$ inflates to sup-norm $\approx 0.12$ in $\mathbb {R}^{32}$). $D(L)$ is the empirical max embedding-diameter over WL-equivalent pairs; $\delta _{L}$ is the lemma's worst-case bound; $\gamma _{\mathrm {eff}}^{(L)} := (D(L)/D(0))^{1/L}$ is the empirical per-round amplification factor, comparable to the worst-case sum-aggregator step $L^{c}_{\ell } + \Delta _{\max } L^{m}_{\ell }$ (here $L^{c}_{\ell } \approx (1{+}\varepsilon )\|W_{\ell }\|_{\rm op}$, $L^{m}_{\ell } \approx \|W_{\ell }\|_{\rm op}$, with the trainable GIN $\varepsilon \approx 0$ at random init). The lemma holds at every sweep point ($\delta _{0} = 0$ recovers strict equality at machine precision); the bound is loose by $6$--$7$ orders of magnitude, because $1+\Delta _{\max }$ is the worst-case fan-in, not the typical one. $\gamma _{\mathrm {eff}} \approx 1.5$--$2.1$ across both graphs and all noise scales --- close to the identity per round --- suggesting that an average-degree (rather than max-degree) refinement of \cref {lem:mpnn-wl-robust} would tighten the bound by roughly $\bigl ((L^{c}{+}\Delta _{\max } L^{m})/\gamma _{\mathrm {eff}}\bigr )^{L}$ on real sparse graphs --- a $\approx 10^{6}\times $ improvement on Cora at $L=3$. We leave such a mean-Lipschitz refinement to future work; raw outputs in \texttt {experiments/results/e3e.json}}{table.8}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e3d@cref}{{[table][8][]8}{[1][22][]23}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3d-arch-full --- Extended sweep: GCN/GAT/GIN/SAGE $\times $ \{Cora, CiteSeer, PubMed, Twitch-EN\}, 5 seeds.}{23}{section*.38}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces E3d-arch: post-hoc architecture-vs-WL audit (mean $\pm $ std over seeds $\{0,1,2\}$). \textbf  {Three clean findings:} \textbf  {(F1) features generically refine WL.} feat\_gap $> 0$ on $23$ of $27$ cells; CiteSeer --- the hardest dataset for any pure 1-WL initialisation (cf.~E3f) --- is rescued by features ($+0.05$ to $+0.06$ bracket-error reduction at matched cell budget, $9/9$ cells). \textbf  {(F2) attention can erase structure.} All three GAT seeds on PubMed give negative feat\_gap ($-0.006$ on average) while GCN/GIN remain positive; the bracket framework cleanly detects an architecture \emph  {failing} to use structural information. \textbf  {(F3) the linear head leaves bracket-detectable structure universally.} Under the corrected sign convention ($\text  {head\_sig} := \hat  R - \varepsilon ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm  {trained}}_{k}}$, P0.3), head\_sig $> 0$ on all $27/27$ cells (mean $+0.046$): per-cell majority on the head's own $k$-means partition would achieve \emph  {lower} error than the trained linear head, so head\_sig quantifies the head-slack $\Delta _{\mathrm  {head}}$ left on the table by a single linear layer. GIN is init-sensitive (Cora seed=0 fails to fit, inflating the GIN/Cora std), which is the largest single contributor to its head\_slack of $+0.182$. MPS is non-bit-deterministic, so per-seed numbers drift on re-run; signs and trends are robust. Raw outputs in \texttt  {experiments/results/e3d\_arch.json}.}}{24}{table.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e3d-arch}{{9}{24}{E3d-arch: post-hoc architecture-vs-WL audit (mean $\pm $ std over seeds $\{0,1,2\}$). \textbf {Three clean findings:} \textbf {(F1) features generically refine WL.} feat\_gap $> 0$ on $23$ of $27$ cells; CiteSeer --- the hardest dataset for any pure 1-WL initialisation (cf.~E3f) --- is rescued by features ($+0.05$ to $+0.06$ bracket-error reduction at matched cell budget, $9/9$ cells). \textbf {(F2) attention can erase structure.} All three GAT seeds on PubMed give negative feat\_gap ($-0.006$ on average) while GCN/GIN remain positive; the bracket framework cleanly detects an architecture \emph {failing} to use structural information. \textbf {(F3) the linear head leaves bracket-detectable structure universally.} Under the corrected sign convention ($\text {head\_sig} := \hat R - \eps ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm {trained}}_{k}}$, P0.3), head\_sig $> 0$ on all $27/27$ cells (mean $+0.046$): per-cell majority on the head's own $k$-means partition would achieve \emph {lower} error than the trained linear head, so head\_sig quantifies the head-slack $\Delta _{\mathrm {head}}$ left on the table by a single linear layer. GIN is init-sensitive (Cora seed=0 fails to fit, inflating the GIN/Cora std), which is the largest single contributor to its head\_slack of $+0.182$. MPS is non-bit-deterministic, so per-seed numbers drift on re-run; signs and trends are robust. Raw outputs in \texttt {experiments/results/e3d\_arch.json}}{table.9}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e3d-arch@cref}{{[table][9][]9}{[1][23][]24}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3d-arch-full --- Synthesis on the 5/5 closure (regime, trichotomy, verdict).}{24}{section*.39}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {10}{\ignorespaces E3d-arch-full: 5-seed, 4-architecture, 4-dataset extension of \cref  {tab:e3d-arch} (total wall $3\,224$ s = CUDA $763$ s for Cora/CiteSeer/PubMed + CPU $2\,461$ s for Twitch-EN). \textbf  {(F1$'$) features generically refine WL --- confirmed at matched $k$.} On the two datasets where evaluation budget \emph  {equals} $k_{\mathrm  {WL}}$ (Cora, CiteSeer), feat\_gap $> 0$ on $8/8$ arch-dataset cells; CiteSeer/SAGE achieves the clean limit $+0.077$ at $\hat  R = 0$ (perfect fit at $n{=}3327$, $k{=}2044$ leaves little label ambiguity inside any cell --- a healthy expected memorisation regime). \textbf  {(F2$'$) GAT erases structure even at hidden width $128$.} PubMed GAT feat\_gap $-0.039 \pm 0.002$ is nearly an order of magnitude more negative than the 3-seed pilot's $-0.006 \pm 0.003$; reproducible failure mode. \textbf  {(F3$'$) head\_sig $> 0$ on all $20/20$ arch-dataset cells} (mean $+0.084$, range $[+0.000, +0.221]$) under the corrected sign convention $\hat  R - \varepsilon ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm  {tr}}_{k}}$ (P0.3): per-cell majority on the trained embedding's $k$-means partition strictly improves on the trained linear head on every cell, so head\_sig is the head-slack $\Delta _{\mathrm  {head}}$ of the $(\star )$ decomposition and is strictly positive everywhere. \emph  {Caveat:} PubMed / Twitch-EN evaluate at $k = 4096 < k_{\mathrm  {WL}}$ so their feat\_gap signs conflate features-vs-WL with $k$-budget mismatch; the Twitch-EN $\hat  R \approx 0.41$ is itself close to the trivial constant baseline ($1 - \pi = 0.454$). Closing the $k$-mismatch is the natural next experiment. \textbf  {Closing the loop on ogbn-arxiv:} the ogbn-arxiv block uses the same evaluation budget caveat ($k=4096<k_{\mathrm  {WL}}=161\,943$); the 5/5 merge is at \texttt  {experiments/results/e3d\_arch\_full.5of5.json}; two-phase split docs in \texttt  {experiments/runpod/README.md}. Raw outputs: \texttt  {experiments/results/e3d\_arch\_full.4of5.json}.}}{25}{table.10}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e3d-arch-full}{{10}{25}{E3d-arch-full: 5-seed, 4-architecture, 4-dataset extension of \cref {tab:e3d-arch} (total wall $3\,224$ s = CUDA $763$ s for Cora/CiteSeer/PubMed + CPU $2\,461$ s for Twitch-EN). \textbf {(F1$'$) features generically refine WL --- confirmed at matched $k$.} On the two datasets where evaluation budget \emph {equals} $k_{\mathrm {WL}}$ (Cora, CiteSeer), feat\_gap $> 0$ on $8/8$ arch-dataset cells; CiteSeer/SAGE achieves the clean limit $+0.077$ at $\hat R = 0$ (perfect fit at $n{=}3327$, $k{=}2044$ leaves little label ambiguity inside any cell --- a healthy expected memorisation regime). \textbf {(F2$'$) GAT erases structure even at hidden width $128$.} PubMed GAT feat\_gap $-0.039 \pm 0.002$ is nearly an order of magnitude more negative than the 3-seed pilot's $-0.006 \pm 0.003$; reproducible failure mode. \textbf {(F3$'$) head\_sig $> 0$ on all $20/20$ arch-dataset cells} (mean $+0.084$, range $[+0.000, +0.221]$) under the corrected sign convention $\hat R - \eps ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm {tr}}_{k}}$ (P0.3): per-cell majority on the trained embedding's $k$-means partition strictly improves on the trained linear head on every cell, so head\_sig is the head-slack $\Delta _{\mathrm {head}}$ of the $(\star )$ decomposition and is strictly positive everywhere. \emph {Caveat:} PubMed / Twitch-EN evaluate at $k = 4096 < k_{\mathrm {WL}}$ so their feat\_gap signs conflate features-vs-WL with $k$-budget mismatch; the Twitch-EN $\hat R \approx 0.41$ is itself close to the trivial constant baseline ($1 - \pi = 0.454$). Closing the $k$-mismatch is the natural next experiment. \textbf {Closing the loop on ogbn-arxiv:} the ogbn-arxiv block uses the same evaluation budget caveat ($k=4096<k_{\mathrm {WL}}=161\,943$); the 5/5 merge is at \texttt {experiments/results/e3d\_arch\_full.5of5.json}; two-phase split docs in \texttt {experiments/runpod/README.md}. Raw outputs: \texttt {experiments/results/e3d\_arch\_full.4of5.json}}{table.10}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e3d-arch-full@cref}{{[table][10][]10}{[1][23][]25}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E3d-arch-kll-n --- Expressivity at $k\ll n$ on Cora/CiteSeer (P0.4).}{25}{section*.40}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E4 --- Cross-architecture duel at fixed cell budget (UCI Adult, $K=16$).}{25}{section*.41}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {11}{\ignorespaces E3d-arch-kll-n (P0.4): $20$ arch-dataset cells at $k \in \{8,16,32,64\} \ll k_{\mathrm  {WL}}$ on Cora ($k/n \le 0.024$) and CiteSeer ($k/n \le 0.019$). Total wall $\approx 869\,$s on CPU. Bold values indicate $\varepsilon ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm  {tr}}_{k}} \le \varepsilon _{\mathrm  {WL}}$ at the same $k$, i.e.\ the trained $k$-cell partition strictly beats the WL ceiling on the full ($k_{\mathrm  {WL}}$-cell) partition --- the clean expressivity finding that the matched-$k$ rows of \cref  {tab:e3d-arch-full} could not deliver, because both sides of the comparison there were inside the cardinality-collapse regime. \textbf  {(F1$''$, expressivity, NEW).} At $k=64$ ($k/n \le 0.024$) on Cora, GAT/GIN/SAGE all achieve $\varepsilon ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm  {tr}}_{64}} \le \varepsilon _{\mathrm  {WL}} = 0.029$; on CiteSeer all four architectures reach $\varepsilon ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm  {tr}}_{64}} \le 0.030 \ll \varepsilon _{\mathrm  {WL}} = 0.078$. The trained embeddings carry label structure that 1-WL at the same cell budget does not --- an expressivity claim, not a memorisation artefact. This \emph  {closes} C2 in its strong form on Cora and CiteSeer. \textbf  {(F2$''$, GAT/SAGE robustness, NEW).} Architecture dependence at fixed $k$ is mild on Cora (GAT $0.019$, GIN $0.024$, GCN $0.029$) and dominated by SAGE's degenerate zero-fit; the F2 ``GAT erases structure'' verdict of \cref  {tab:e3d-arch-full} was a $k\!=\!4096$ PubMed artefact, not a feature of the $k \ll n$ regime tested here. \textbf  {(F3$''$, head-slack, NEW).} The head-slack $\Delta _{\mathrm  {head}}$ collapses to zero at $k=64$ (magnitudes $\le 0.017$, signs mixed) but is non-trivially \emph  {negative} at $k=8$ on GIN/SAGE ($-0.034$, $-0.005$ to $-0.077$): at very coarse budgets MiniBatchKMeans produces a partition whose per-cell-majority error \emph  {exceeds} the trained head's, so the head extracts continuous-$Z$ geometry that the coarse partition discards. \textbf  {F3$'$ from \cref  {tab:e3d-arch-full} is therefore restated:} the universal-positive-head-slack reading was a matched-$k$ ($k=k_{\mathrm  {WL}}$) phenomenon; at $k \ll n$ the sign is $k$-dependent and architecture-dependent. SAGE on Cora is exactly zero everywhere because the model fits perfectly ($\hat  R = 0$) and the features are linearly separable regardless of the cell-budget choice. Raw outputs in \texttt  {experiments/results/e3d\_arch\_kll\_n.json}; verifier \texttt  {experiments/e3d\_arch\_kll\_n.py}.}}{26}{table.11}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e3d-arch-kll-n}{{11}{26}{E3d-arch-kll-n (P0.4): $20$ arch-dataset cells at $k \in \{8,16,32,64\} \ll k_{\mathrm {WL}}$ on Cora ($k/n \le 0.024$) and CiteSeer ($k/n \le 0.019$). Total wall $\approx 869\,$s on CPU. Bold values indicate $\eps ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm {tr}}_{k}} \le \eps _{\mathrm {WL}}$ at the same $k$, i.e.\ the trained $k$-cell partition strictly beats the WL ceiling on the full ($k_{\mathrm {WL}}$-cell) partition --- the clean expressivity finding that the matched-$k$ rows of \cref {tab:e3d-arch-full} could not deliver, because both sides of the comparison there were inside the cardinality-collapse regime. \textbf {(F1$''$, expressivity, NEW).} At $k=64$ ($k/n \le 0.024$) on Cora, GAT/GIN/SAGE all achieve $\eps ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm {tr}}_{64}} \le \eps _{\mathrm {WL}} = 0.029$; on CiteSeer all four architectures reach $\eps ^{*}_{\Pi ^{\mathrm {tr}}_{64}} \le 0.030 \ll \eps _{\mathrm {WL}} = 0.078$. The trained embeddings carry label structure that 1-WL at the same cell budget does not --- an expressivity claim, not a memorisation artefact. This \emph {closes} C2 in its strong form on Cora and CiteSeer. \textbf {(F2$''$, GAT/SAGE robustness, NEW).} Architecture dependence at fixed $k$ is mild on Cora (GAT $0.019$, GIN $0.024$, GCN $0.029$) and dominated by SAGE's degenerate zero-fit; the F2 ``GAT erases structure'' verdict of \cref {tab:e3d-arch-full} was a $k\!=\!4096$ PubMed artefact, not a feature of the $k \ll n$ regime tested here. \textbf {(F3$''$, head-slack, NEW).} The head-slack $\Delta _{\mathrm {head}}$ collapses to zero at $k=64$ (magnitudes $\le 0.017$, signs mixed) but is non-trivially \emph {negative} at $k=8$ on GIN/SAGE ($-0.034$, $-0.005$ to $-0.077$): at very coarse budgets MiniBatchKMeans produces a partition whose per-cell-majority error \emph {exceeds} the trained head's, so the head extracts continuous-$Z$ geometry that the coarse partition discards. \textbf {F3$'$ from \cref {tab:e3d-arch-full} is therefore restated:} the universal-positive-head-slack reading was a matched-$k$ ($k=k_{\mathrm {WL}}$) phenomenon; at $k \ll n$ the sign is $k$-dependent and architecture-dependent. SAGE on Cora is exactly zero everywhere because the model fits perfectly ($\hat R = 0$) and the features are linearly separable regardless of the cell-budget choice. Raw outputs in \texttt {experiments/results/e3d\_arch\_kll\_n.json}; verifier \texttt {experiments/e3d\_arch\_kll\_n.py}}{table.11}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e3d-arch-kll-n@cref}{{[table][11][]11}{[1][25][]26}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {12}{\ignorespaces E4: the supervised tree dominates the unsupervised quantiser at equal cell budget. Figure: \texttt  {experiments/figures/e4\_duel\_table.pdf}.}}{26}{table.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e4}{{12}{26}{E4: the supervised tree dominates the unsupervised quantiser at equal cell budget. Figure: \texttt {experiments/figures/e4\_duel\_table.pdf}}{table.12}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e4@cref}{{[table][12][]12}{[1][25][]26}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E5 --- Achievable-region scatter (synthetic).}{26}{section*.42}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{toc}{\contentsline {paragraph}{E6 NAS --- bracket as a training-free architecture pre-filter.}{26}{section*.43}\protected@file@percent }
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {13}{\ignorespaces E6 NAS: bracket as a training-free architecture pre-filter. Five gates: G1 (CI excludes zero on both datasets) \emph  {fails} (Adult passes, digits-bin does not); G2 (bracket beats parameter count) \emph  {passes} on both --- parameter count is in fact \emph  {strongly negatively} correlated with test error here, so the standard NAS prior actively misranks; G3 (top-5 by bracket beats uniform random) \emph  {passes} on both; G4 (end-to-end speedup $\ge 10\times $) \emph  {fails} at this menu size; G5 (test-error spread $\ge 5$ pp, i.e.\ the menu is worth ranking at all) \emph  {passes} on both ($11.1$ pp and $36.8$ pp).}}{27}{table.13}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:e6nas}{{13}{27}{E6 NAS: bracket as a training-free architecture pre-filter. Five gates: G1 (CI excludes zero on both datasets) \emph {fails} (Adult passes, digits-bin does not); G2 (bracket beats parameter count) \emph {passes} on both --- parameter count is in fact \emph {strongly negatively} correlated with test error here, so the standard NAS prior actively misranks; G3 (top-5 by bracket beats uniform random) \emph {passes} on both; G4 (end-to-end speedup $\ge 10\times $) \emph {fails} at this menu size; G5 (test-error spread $\ge 5$ pp, i.e.\ the menu is worth ranking at all) \emph {passes} on both ($11.1$ pp and $36.8$ pp)}{table.13}{}}
\newlabel{tab:e6nas@cref}{{[table][13][]13}{[1][27][]27}{}{}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces E6-NAS: lower bracket endpoint vs.\ held-out test error (left) and Kendall-$\tau $ comparison vs.\ parameter count (right) on a heterogeneous $35$-architecture menu over UCI Adult ($n_{\mathrm  {tr}} = 36{,}177$). The bracket attains $\tau = 0.48$ ($p = 5{\times }10^{-5}$) with held-out test error; parameter count \emph  {anti}-ranks at $\tau = -0.38$. The companion digits-bin row ($n_{\mathrm  {tr}} = 1{,}437$, $\tau = +0.11$, CI crosses zero) is plotted in the JSON-only v2 artefact; it is the predicted small-$n$ failure regime of \cref  {prop:pop} and is reported in \cref  {tab:e6nas}.}}{27}{figure.4}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:e6nas}{{4}{27}{E6-NAS: lower bracket endpoint vs.\ held-out test error (left) and Kendall-$\tau $ comparison vs.\ parameter count (right) on a heterogeneous $35$-architecture menu over UCI Adult ($n_{\mathrm {tr}} = 36{,}177$). The bracket attains $\tau = 0.48$ ($p = 5{\times }10^{-5}$) with held-out test error; parameter count \emph {anti}-ranks at $\tau = -0.38$. The companion digits-bin row ($n_{\mathrm {tr}} = 1{,}437$, $\tau = +0.11$, CI crosses zero) is plotted in the JSON-only v2 artefact; it is the predicted small-$n$ failure regime of \cref {prop:pop} and is reported in \cref {tab:e6nas}}{figure.4}{}}
\newlabel{fig:e6nas@cref}{{[figure][4][]4}{[1][27][]27}{}{}{}}
